      "story_cards": [
        {
          "title": "Russell Controls",
          "body": "George Russell converted pole into a composed lights-to-flag victory. He managed both VSC periods perfectly — pitting on Lap 19 and Lap 34 for free stops onto the hard compound. The second set of hards gave him the pace to pull clear of Antonelli in the final stint, and he crossed the line 2.974 seconds clear. Never truly challenged, never under pressure."
        },
        {
          "title": "Antonelli's Historic P2",
          "body": "Kimi Antonelli, 18, became the youngest driver in Formula 1 history to finish on the podium on their race debut. Starting second, he led briefly when Russell pitted under VSC 1, before pitting himself. His pace on the hard tyre in the final stint was strong but not quite Russell-level. Crucially, he made no mistakes on a circuit where rookies routinely find the barriers."
        },
        {
          "title": "Ferrari's VSC Disaster",
          "body": "Leclerc led through Turn 1 as Russell made a slow start, and looked set to pressure Mercedes. Then the VSC periods arrived and Ferrari stayed out both times while Mercedes pitted for free stops. It was a catastrophic call, handing Russell fresh tyres at zero cost while leaving Leclerc on degrading rubber. He dropped from the lead to P3. 'We made the wrong call both times,' Leclerc said post-race."
        },
        {
          "title": "Verstappen's Recovery",
          "body": "Max Verstappen started 20th after crashing at Turn 1 in Q1 — the same corner that has caught him repeatedly at Albert Park. He set the fastest lap of the race on Lap 43 and charged from the back to P6, passing multiple cars on a circuit notorious for its inability to facilitate overtaking. Oscar Piastri couldn't start at all — a Turn 4 crash on the sighting lap made him the fourth driver in F1 history to retire before the formation lap."
        }
      ],

      "insights": [
        {
          "type": "win",
          "icon": "🏆",
          "headline": "The W17 Is a Different Machine",
          "body": "Russell's comfortable 2.974-second victory against the fastest qualifying grid in recent F1 history was a statement of intent. The W17 clearly has strong raw pace over a single lap (pole by 0.293s over Antonelli) and race pace that was visibly superior to Ferrari and McLaren on the hard compound. Mercedes' winter development has produced the benchmark car for 2026."
        },
        {
          "type": "strategy",
          "icon": "📋",
          "headline": "Ferrari's VSC Paralysis",
          "body": "Staying out under a VSC period when the race leader pits is almost never the correct call in modern F1. The VSC delta eliminates the pit stop time loss, making the stop effectively free. Ferrari did it twice in the same race. That kind of double strategic failure at Round 1 suggests structural issues in the decision-making process that go beyond one bad afternoon."
        },
        {
          "type": "history",
          "icon": "⭐",
          "headline": "Antonelli's Instant Impact",
          "body": "P2 on debut at 18 years old isn't just a headline — it's a statement. Hamilton took until Round 3 to reach the podium. Leclerc scored P5 on debut. Verstappen won on debut, but at a circuit he'd tested extensively. Antonelli navigated traffic, tyre management, and a direct comparison with Russell in the same car. He looked like a driver in his fifth season, not his first grand prix."
        },
        {
          "type": "crash",
